A stack is a linear data structure where the topmost element is the last one added to the stack, and the bottommost element is the first one added to the stack. It is also known as a Last In First Out (LIFO) data structure. The key feature of a stack is that it allows us to access the data in the reverse order of its insertion. This makes it ideal for implementing algorithms that require us to perform operations on the stack in a specific order, such as the ones that need to pop the topmost element off the stack or find the maximum element in a stack.

A common way to implement a stack data structure in Java is to use an array of objects, where the first element of the array is used as the "top" of the stack, and the remaining elements are used to store the elements in the stack in the reverse order. Whenever we want to push a new element onto the stack, we simply add it to the end of the array, and when we want to pop an element off the stack, we simply remove the first element from the array and return it. Here is a simple Java code snippet that demonstrates how to implement a stack using an array:

```java
public class StackDemo {
    private static final int DEFAULT_CAPACITY = 10;
    private int[] stack;
    private int top;

    public StackDemo() {
        this.stack = new int[DEFAULT_CAPACITY];
        this.top = -1;
    }

    public void push(int val) {
        if (top < 0) {
            top = stack.length - 1;
        } else {
            System.out.println("Stack is full, cannot push element " + val);
        }
        stack[top] = val;
    }

    public int pop() {
        if (top < 0) {
            System.out.println("Stack is empty, cannot pop element");
        } else {
            top--;
            return stack[top];
        }
    }

    public int peek() {
        if (top < 0) {
            System.out.println("Stack is empty, cannot peek element");
        } else {
            return stack[top];
        }
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return top < 0;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        StackDemo stackDemo = new StackDemo();

        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            stackDemo.push(i);
        }

        System.out.println(stackDemo.pop());
        System.out.println(stackDemo.peek());
        System.out.println(stackDemo.isEmpty());

        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            System.out.println(stackDemo.pop());
        }
    }
}

